{{For|the neighbourhood in Istanbul|Beylerbeyi}}
'''''Beylerbey''''' or '''''Beylerbeyi''''' ({{lang-ota|بكلربكی}}; "[[Bey]] of Beys", meaning "the Commander of Commanders" or "the Lord of Lords"; originally '''''Beglerbeg[i]''''' in older [[Turkic languages|Turkic]]) was a high rank in the western Islamic world in the late [[Middle Ages]] and [[early modern period]], from the [[Seljuks of Rum]] and the [[Ilkhanids]] to [[Safavid Persia]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]]. Initially designating a [[commander-in-chief]], it eventually came to be held by senior provincial governors. In Ottoman usage, where the rank survived the longest, it designated the governors-general of some of the largest and most important provinces, although in later centuries it became devalued into a mere honorific title. Its equivalents in [[Arabic]] were ''[[amir al-umara]]'', and in Persian, ''mir-i miran''.

The title was also used by the Khans of the Indian (later Pakistani) [[Kalat (princely state)|princely state of Kalat]].

== Early use ==
The title originated with the [[Seljuqs]], and was used in the [[Sultanate of Rum]] initially as an alternative for the Arabic title of ''[[malik]] al-umara'' ("chief of the commanders"), designating the army's commander-in-chief.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}} Among the [[Mongols|Mongol]] [[Ilkhanids]], the title was used to designate the chief ''[[amir]] al-ulus'' ("emir of the state")—also known by the Turkic title ''ulusbegi'' and the Arabic ''[[amir al-umara]]''–while in the [[Golden Horde]] it was applied to all the holders of the rank of ''amir al-ulus''.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}{{sfn|Jackson|1989|p=84}} The [[Mamluks of Egypt]] possibly used it as an alternative title for the ''[[atabak]] al-asakir'', the commander-in-chief of the army.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}

== Ottoman use ==
{{further|Subdivisions of the Ottoman Empire}}
The Ottomans used the title from the late 14th until the mid-19th century, with varying meanings and degrees of importance.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}} The early Ottoman state continued to use the term ''beylerbey'' in the meaning of commander-in-chief, held by princes of the [[Ottoman dynasty]]: under the Ottoman Empire's founder, [[Osman I]] (ruled 1299–1326), his son [[Orhan I|Orhan]] held the post, and during Orhan's reign (1324–1362), his brother [[Alaeddin Pasha]] and Orhan's son [[Süleyman Pasha (son of Orhan)|Süleyman Pasha]].{{sfn|Birken|1976|pp=8–9}}{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|p=722}}

The first step towards the transformation of the office into a gubernatorial title occurred when the title was given by [[Murad I]] (r. 1362–89) to [[Lala Shahin Pasha]], as a reward for his [[Ottoman capture of Adrianople|capture of Adrianople]] (modern [[Edirne]]) in the 1360s. In addition, Lala Shahin was given military authority over the Ottoman territories in Europe ([[Rumelia]]).{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|p=722}} This marked the ''beylerbey'' effectively as the [[viceroy]] of the European territories as the [[Ottoman Sultan|Sultans]] still resided in [[Anatolia]], and as the straits of the [[Bosporus]] and the [[Dardanelles]], which connected the two parts of the Ottoman state, continued to escape full Ottoman control until the [[Fall of Constantinople]] in 1453.{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|p=722}}

After Lala Shahin's death, sometime in 1385–87 he was succeeded in the position of commander-in-chief in Rumelia by [[Çandarlı Kara Halil Hayreddin Pasha]]. In 1393, Sultan [[Bayezid I]] (r. 1389–1402) appointed [[Kara Timurtash]] as ''beylerbey''  and viceroy was in Anatolia, when Bayezid crossed over into Europe to campaign against [[Mircea I of Wallachia]].{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|p=722}} This process marked the birth of the first two, and by far the most important, ''[[Eyalet|beylerbeyliks]]'', of [[Rumelia Eyalet|Rumelia]] and [[Anatolia Eyalet|Anatolia]], while the third ''beylerbeylik'', that of [[Rûm Eyalet|Rûm]], followed soon after.{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|p=722}}

[[File:Ottoman Empire (1609).png|thumb|200px|The ''eyalets'' of the Ottoman Empire in 1609]]
The ''beylerbey'' was in charge of a province—termed ''beylerbeylik'' or generically ''vilayet'', "province", while after 1591 the term ''[[eyalet]]'' was used and ''beylerbeylik'' came to mean the office of ''beylerbey''{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|pp=721–722, 723}}—further subdivided into ''[[sanjak]]s'' or ''"liwa"s'' under ''[[sanjakbey]]s''.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}{{sfn|Birken|1976|pp=8–9}} With the continuous [[growth of the Ottoman Empire]] in the 15th and 16th centuries, new provinces were established, and the ranks of the ''beylerbeys'' swelled to a maximum of 44 by the end of the 16th century.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}{{sfn|Birken|1976|p=9}} A list of ''eyalets'' in 1609 mentions 32 in total, of which 23 regular ''eyalets'' where revenue was distributed among the military fief-holders, while the rest (in [[North Africa]] and the [[Middle East]]) were under the ''[[salyane]]'' system, i.e. their revenue was sent to the imperial treasury, and the officials and soldiers were paid salaries from it.{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|p=723}} The size of these new provinces varied enormously: some containing as many as twenty ''sanjaks'', and others as few as two, including the ''beylerbey''{{'}}s own residence (or ''[[pasha]]-sanjakı'').{{sfn|Birken|1976|p=9}} Among themselves, the various ''beylerbeys'' had an order of precedence based on the date of conquest or formation of their provinces. The ''beylerbey'' of Rumelia, however, retained his pre-eminence, ranking first among the other provincial governors-general, and being accorded a seat in the [[Imperial Council (Ottoman Empire)|Imperial Council]] (''[[divan]]'') after 1536. In addition, the post was occasionally held by the Sultan's chief minister, the [[Grand Vizier]] himself.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|p=722}}

[[File:Ralamb - 103 - Beylerbey of Bosnia.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Depiction of the ''beylerbey'' of the [[Bosnia Eyalet]] (1657)]]
In his province, the ''beylerbey'' was regarded as a virtual viceroy of the Sultan: he had full authority over matters of war, justice and administration, except in so far as they were limited by the authority of other officials also appointed by the central government, chiefly the various fiscal secretaries under the ''mal defterdari'' and the ''[[kadı]]'', who could appeal directly to the imperial government. In addition, as a further check to their power, the [[Janissary]] contingents stationed in the province's cities were outside his authority, and ''beylerbeys'' were even forbidden from entering the fortresses garrisoned by the Janissaries.{{sfn|Birken|1976|pp=10–11}}{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|p=723}} The ''beylerbey'' also had his own court and government council (''divan'') and could freely grant fiefs (''[[timar]]s'' and ''[[ziamet]]s'') without prior approval by the Sultan, although this right was curtailed after 1530, when his authority was restricted to smaller ''timars'' only.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}} Having its origin in the military, the primary responsibility of the ''beylerbeys'' and their ''sanjakbeys'' was the maintenance the ''[[sipahi]]'' cavalry, formed by the holders of the military fiefs, whom they led in person on campaign.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}{{sfn|İnalcık|1965|pp=722, 723}}

From the reign of [[Mehmed II]] (r. 1451–1481) onwards, the title of ''beylerbey'' also became an honorary court rank, coming after the viziers; both viziers and ''beylerbeys'' were titled [[pasha]]s, with the viziers sporting three [[tugh|horse-tails]] and the ''beylerbeys'' two.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}} From the 16th century on, however, viziers could be appointed as provincial ''beylerbeys'', enjoying precedence and authority over the ordinary ''beylerbeys'' of the neighbouring provinces.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}} Towards the end of the 17th century, the title of ''beylerbey'' of Rumelia (''Rumeli beylerbeysi'') also began to be awarded as an honorific rank, alongside the actual holder of the provincial post, even to officials unrelated to the provincial administration, such as the chief treasurer (''[[defterdar]]'').{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}{{sfn|Birken|1976|p=9}}

Beginning in the 18th century, the Arabic title of ''[[wali]]'' began to be increasingly used for provincial governors-general at the expense of ''beylerbey'', except for the two original ''beylerbeys'' of Rumelia and Anatolia; the Arabic title ''amir al-umara'', and the Persian ''mir-i miran'' or ''mirmiran'', which had been used as equivalents of the ''beylerbey'', now increasingly came to refer only to the honorary rank, which in turn was increasingly devalued. The process culminated with the ''[[vilayet]]'' reform of 1864, after which ''wali'' became the only official designation for the governor-general of a province, while the title of ''beylerbey'' survived only in the honorary rank of ''Rumeli beylerbeysi'', which continued in use alongside its Perso-Arabian equivalents.{{sfn|Ménage|1960|pp=1159–1160}}

== Safavid use ==
{{see|Beylerbeylik (Safavid Persia)}}
[[Image:Daud Khan Undiladze.jpg|thumb|[[Daud Khan Undiladze]], [[ghilman]] and the beylerbey of [[Ganja, Azerbaijan|Ganja]] and [[Karabakh]] from 1625 to 1630.]]
Under the [[Safavid dynasty]] of [[Persia]], the title was used from ca. 1543/44 on for governors (generically styled ''[[hakim (title)|hakim]]'') of the more important provinces. The title was thus used for the governors of [[Herat]], [[Azerbaijan]], [[Ganja, Azerbaijan|Ganja]], [[Karabakh]], [[Shirvan]], [[Fars (East Syrian Ecclesiastical Province)|Fars]], [[Iraq]], and [[Astarabad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=kwpHHr4CMWQC&pg=PA109&dq=beylerbeyi+safavid&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=d9-gVO6JHqbC7gaTr4CYCQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=beylerbeyi%20safavid&f=false|title=My Road of Life|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> The Safavids also used the title of ''wali'' for provinces even more important than those of ''beylerbeys''. Towards the end of the Safavid period, the title of ''beylerbey'' had been eclipsed by that of ''wali'', most notably being the wali's of the shah's their [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] lands.{{sfn|Jackson|1989|p=84}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/georgia-vii-|title=GEORGIA vii. Georgians in the Safavid Administration|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>

