'''Luis Rebolledo de Palafox y Melci, 1st [[marquis|marqués]] de Lazán''' (June 2, 1772, [[Zaragoza]] &ndash; December 28, 1843, [[Madrid]]) was an [[Spain|Aragonese]] [[officer (military)|officer]] and [[general]] during the [[Peninsular War|Spanish War of Independence]]. Alongside his brother [[José de Palafox y Melzi, Duke of Saragossa|José de Palafox]], the ''Duke of Saragossa'', Lazán was a [[Folk hero|national hero]] in 19th century Spain for his [[Siege of Saragossa (1809)|defence of Saragossa]] from the [[France|French]] [[First French Empire|Imperial]] armies in 1808 and 1809.
Lazán was born to Juan Felipe Rebolledo de Palafox and [[doña]] Paula Melci de Eril and educated at the ''[[Escuelas Pías]]'' in [[Zaragoza]]. In 1809 he commanded an army in the campaign for [[Catalonia]], winning a notable success at [[Battle of Castellón|Castellón]]. Upon the [[Mid-nineteenth century Spain|restoration]] of [[Ferdinand VII of Spain|Ferdinand VII]] to the [[Spanish Crown]] in 1814 ([[Treaty of Valençay]]), Lazán aligned himself with the [[reactionary]] party defending Ferdinand's [[absolute monarchy]] and opposing the [[liberalism|liberal]] [[Spanish Constitution of 1812|Constitution of 1812]]. From 1815 to 1820 Lazán served as [[Captain General]] of [[Aragon]].
