'''#NotAllMen''' is a popular [[Internet meme]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Ferdy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/thinking-man/10924854/Is-there-a-misogynist-inside-every-man.html |title=Is there a misogynist inside every man? |website=[[Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |location=London, England|date=2 July 2014|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=jezebel/> It is a shortened [[hashtag]] version of the phrase '''not all men are like that''',<ref>{{cite news|first=Mina|last=Malik-Hussain|url=http://www.nation.com.pk/columns/02-Jun-2014/clapping-with-both-hands|title=Clapping with Both Hands|work=[[The Nation (Pakistan)|The Nation]]||publisher=Nawa-i-Waqt Group of Publications|location=Karachi, Pakistan|date=June 2, 2014|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref> sometimes abbreviated '''NAMALT'''.

A [[Time magazine|''Time'' magazine]] article on the subject states that "Not all men" was previously stated as an object of frustration, but in early 2014 it became usually used as an object of mockery. Intended to counter [[generalization]]s about men’s behavior, the phrase has been criticized for deflecting conversations from uncomfortable topics, such as [[sexual assault]].<ref name="Jess Zimmerman">{{cite web|first=Jess|last=Zimmerman |url=http://time.com/79357/not-all-men-a-brief-history-of-every-dudes-favorite-argument/ |title=Not All Men: A Brief History of Every Dude's Favorite Argument |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Michel|last1=Martin|first2=Arthur|last2= Chu|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/05/30/317361633/jeopardy-champ-arthur-chu-on-nerds-entitlement-and-elliot-rodger|title=Jeopardy Champ Arthur Chu On Nerds, Entitlement And Elliot Rodger |work=[[NPR]]|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref>

==Origin==
[[Vox (website)|Vox]] states that the phrase "not all men are like that," as a general defense of men in gendered criticisms of their behavior, has been around for more than a decade.<ref name="vox.com">{{cite web|first=Kelsey|last=McKinney|title=Here's why women have turned the "not all men" objection into a meme|url=https://www.vox.com/2014/5/15/5720332/heres-why-women-have-turned-the-not-all-men-objection-into-a-meme|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>{{efn|It has been used as early as 1836 in author [[Charles Dickens]]' book ''The Pickwick Papers'', in which, in response to the statement "Men are such deceivers" by Miss Wardle, Mr. Tupman replies "They are, they are, but not all men."<ref>{{cite book|first=Charles|last=Dickens|authorlink=Charles Dickens|title=The Pickwick Papers|publisher=Hueber|location=Munich, Germany|date=1905|isbn=978-1718847675|title-link=The Pickwick Papers}}</ref>}} Before 2013, "not all men" was not seen as a derailment tactic; the most common strategies cited by feminist bloggers were "'what about the men?' and 'patriarchy hurts men too'—pleas for inclusion, not for exemption".<ref name="Jess Zimmerman"/> Jasmine Bailey says the "not all men" argument "seemingly began as a sincere way to counter feminist arguments".<ref>{{cite web|first=Jasmine|last=Bailey|title=What’s up with the #YesAllWomen and #NotAllMen hashtags?|url=http://www.springfieldnewssun.com/news/news/whats-yesallwomen-and-notallmen-hashtags/nf7LF/|website=[[Springfield News-Sun]]|publisher=[[Cox Enterprises]]|location=Springfield, Ohio|date=May 25, 2014|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref> #NotAllMen, however, is often impugned by [[feminists]].  The #NotAllMen [[Twitter]] hashtag was tweeted as early as 2011. The first viral tweet with this phrase, which was not yet a hashtag, was a satirical tweet by Shafiqah Hudson in February 2013: "ME: Men and boys are socially instructed to not listen to us. They are taught to interrupt us when we- RANDOM MAN: Excuse me. Not ALL men."<ref name="vox.com"/><ref>{{cite tweet|user=sassycrass|author=Shafiquah Hudson|number=304432121223716864|title=ME: Men and boys are socially instructed to not listen to us. They are taught to interrupt us when we- RANDOM MAN: Excuse me. Not ALL men.|date=20 February 2013|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref> The stereotypical "Not-All-Man", barging into a conversation criticizing male behavior, was caricatured in a comic by artist Matt Lubchansky on April 14, 2014.<ref name="Jess Zimmerman"/><ref name="vox.com"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Matt|last=Lubchansky|title=Save Me|website = Please Listen to Me|url=http://www.listen-tome.com/save-me/|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Lubchansky’s comic was quickly retweeted and otherwise shared by several male celebrities including [[Wil Wheaton]], [[Paul F. Tompkins]], [[Matt Fraction]], and [[John Scalzi]].<ref name="Jess Zimmerman"/>

==2014 Isla Vista killings==
{{see also|2014 Isla Vista killings|YesAllWomen}}

<nowiki>#</nowiki>NotAllMen was already a [[Twitter]] [[hashtag]] created by the Twitter user Sassycrass before the [[2014 Isla Vista killings]], but it gained additional traction after the event, because of the hatred against women expressed by the shooter, [[Elliot Rodger]]. In response to the hashtag #NotAllMen, an anonymous female Twitter user created the hashtag #YesAllWomen, to express that all women are affected by sexism and [[misogyny]], even though not all men are sexist. This newly created hashtag quickly became used by women throughout social media to share their experiences of sexual discrimination and attacks.<ref>For coverage of this topic, see the following sources:
* {{cite web|first=Jess|last=Zimmerman |url=http://time.com/79357/not-all-men-a-brief-history-of-every-dudes-favorite-argument/ |title=Not All Men Meme Rise of Defense Against Sexism Misogyny |website=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=July 13, 2014}}
* {{cite web|first=Jeff|last=Bridges |url=http://time.com/2809276/notallmen-dont-get-it/ |title=#NotAllMen Don't Get It |website=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=June 2, 2014 |accessdate=July 13, 2014}}
* {{cite web|first=Phil|last=Plait |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2014/05/27/not_all_men_how_discussing_women_s_issues_gets_derailed.html |title=Not all men: How discussing women’s issues gets derailed |website=[[Slate.com]] |publisher=[[The Slate Group]]|location=New York City|date=May 27, 2014 |accessdate=July 13, 2014}}
* {{cite web|first=Monica|last=Vendituoli |url=http://chronicle.com/article/NotAllMen-but-YesAllWomen-/146811/ |title=#NotAllMen, but #YesAllWomen: Campus Tragedy Spurs Debate on Sexual Violence |website=[[Chronicle of Higher Education]]|publisher=The Chronicle of Higher Education Inc.|location=Washington DC|date=May 28, 2014 |accessdate=July 13, 2014}}
* {{Cite news|first=Pete|last = Pachal|url = http://mashable.com/2014/05/26/yesallwomen-hashtag/|title = How the #YesAllWomen Hashtag Began|date = 26 May 2014|work = [[Mashable]]|accessdate = 6 June 2014}}
* {{cite news|title=#YesAllWomen Puts Spotlight On Misogyny|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=28 May 2014}}
* {{Cite news||first = Kelsey|last = McKinney|url = https://www.vox.com/2014/5/15/5720332/heres-why-women-have-turned-the-not-all-men-objection-into-a-meme|title = Here’s why women have turned the "not all men" objection into a meme|date = 15 May 2014|work = Vox|accessdate = 12 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="jezebel"/><ref name="valenti">{{cite web|first=Jessica|last=Valenti|title=#YesAllWomen reveals the constant barrage of sexism that women face|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/may/28/yesallwomen-barage-sexism-elliot-rodger|website=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]location=London, England|date=28 May 2014|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="Plait">{{Cite news|first=Phil|last = Plait|url = http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2014/05/27/not_all_men_how_discussing_women_s_issues_gets_derailed.html|title = #YesAllWomen|work = [[Slate.com]]|publisher=[[The Slate Group]]|location=New York City|date = 27 May 2014|accessdate = 12 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="Grinberg">{{Cite news|first=Emmanuel|last = Grinberg|url = http://www.cnn.com/2014/05/27/living/california-killer-hashtag-yesallwomen/|title = Why #YesAllWomen took off on Twitter|work = [[CNN]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|date = May 27, 2014|accessdate = June 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Dempsey">{{Cite news|first=Amy|last = Dempsey|url = https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2014/05/26/yesallwomen_hashtag_sparks_revelations_anger_debate_in_wake_of_california_killing_spree.html|title = #YesAllWomen hashtag sparks revelations, anger, debate in wake of California killing spree|date = 26 May 2014|work = Toronto Star|accessdate = 12 June 2014}}</ref> Following the killing spree, the attacker’s Internet activity was described as misogynistic, and hatred of women was cited as a factor in the killing spree.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Killer’s Manifesto Reveals Wide Reach Of Misogyny Online|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/05/27/316452303/a-killers-manifesto-reveals-wide-reach-of-misogyny-online|accessdate=18 July 2014|publisher=NPR|date=27 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Irin|last=Carmon|title=Elliot Rodger’s war on women|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/elliot-rodger-war-women-yesallwomen-hashtag|publisher=[[MSNBC]]|date=24 May 2014|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dvorak|first1=Petula|title=#YesAllWomen: Elliot Rodger’s misogynistic ravings inspire a powerful response on Twitter|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/yesallwomen-elliott-rodgers-misogynistic-ravings-inspire-a-powerful-response-on-twitter/2014/05/26/dd755e4e-e4e0-11e3-8f90-73e071f3d637_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington DC|date=May 26, 2014|accessdate=July 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Linda|last=Kelsey|title=Inside the world of the woman haters: The terrifyingly misogynistic websites that fuelled the rage of the virgin killer - and how their poison’s spreading to Britain|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2643262/Inside-world-woman-haters-The-terrifyingly-misogynistic-websites-fuelled-rage-virgin-killer-poisons-spreading-Britain.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=30 May 2014|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Ryan|last=Buxton|title=Elliot Rodger’s Misogynist Manifesto Is 'Familiar' To All Women, Professor Says|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/29/elliot-rodger-misogynist-manifesto_n_5412958.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[Huffington Post Media Group]]|location=New York City|date=May 29, 2014|accessdate=July 18, 2014}}</ref> In the wake of the killings, some Twitter users pointed out the fact that "not all men" are like this, or would commit such crimes.<ref name="Plait"/><ref name="Grinberg"/><ref name="Dempsey"/>

==Bengaluru incident==

After reports of a mass molestation occurring at India’s Bengaluru New Year’s Eve celebration, #NotAllMen began trending on Twitter. This drew an angry reaction from women, with many Indian feminists and women strongly criticizing the hashtag while responding with their own hashtag #YesAllWomen.<ref>{{cite web|first=Arielle|last=De Bono|url= http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/news-and-views/yesallwomen-resurfaces-in-india-in-the-wake-of-mass-molestation-20170104-gtm76i.html?deviceType=text | title = #YesAllWomen resurfaces in India in the wake of mass molestation|website=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|location=Sydney, Australia| date= 8 January 2017|accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Annanya|last=Bhattacharya|url= https://qz.com/876967/notallmen-is-not-an-appropriate-response-to-a-mob-molesting-scores-of-women-in-indias-silicon-valley/ | title = #NotAllMen is not an appropriate response to a mob molesting scores of women in India’s Silicon Valley| website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz India]]|publisher=[[Atlantic Media]]|location=New York City|date= 8 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Andre|last=Borges|url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/andreborges/women-are-hitting-back-at-the-not-all-men-response-to-the-ma | title = People Are Furious At The "Not All Men" Response To The Mass Molestation In Bengaluru On NYE | website=[[Buzzfeed]]|date= 8 January 2017}}</ref>

==Usage==

As Kelsey McKinney of [[Vox (website)|Vox]] states, "The phrase has been reappropriated by feminists and turned into a meme meant to parody its pervasiveness and bad faith."<ref name="vox.com"/> #NotAllMen-related memes include references to [[Aquaman]], ''[[Adventure Time]]'', ''[[Magic: The Gathering]]'', and the [[Kool Aid Man]] crashing through a wall to exclaim "not all men".<ref name="jezebel">{{cite web|title=Your Guide to 'Not All Men,' the Best Meme on the Internet|website= [[Jezebel.com]]|author=Erin Gloria Ryan |url=http://jezebel.com/your-guide-to-not-all-men-the-best-meme-on-the-interne-1573535818|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> An explanation of the NotAllMen hashtag came from Hillary Di Menna of ''[[This (Canadian magazine)|This Magazine]]'', who claimed that: "Saying 'not all men' is not helpful. We need to listen and we need to reflect."<ref>{{cite web|last=Menna |first=Hillary Di |url=http://this.org/blog/2014/07/14/gender-block-slutwalk-toronto-2014/ |title=Gender Block: SlutWalk Toronto 2014 &#124; This Magazine |publisher=This.org |date=2011-04-03 |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref> [[Slate Magazine]] writer Phil Plait wrote that the hashtag was {{Quote|not an unexpected response. However, it’s also not a helpful one. Why is it not helpful to say "not all men are like that"?  For lots of reasons. For one, women know this. They already know not every man is a rapist, or a murderer, or violent. They don’t need you to tell them. Second, it’s defensive. When people are defensive, they aren’t listening to the other person; they’re busy thinking of ways to defend themselves. I watched this happen on Twitter, over and again. Third, the people saying it aren’t furthering the conversation, they’re sidetracking it. The discussion isn’t about the men who aren’t a problem. (Though, I’ll note, it can be. I’ll get back to that.) Instead of being defensive and distracting from the topic at hand, try staying quiet for a while and actually listening to what the thousands upon thousands of women discussing this are saying. Fourth—and this is important, so listen carefully—when a woman is walking down the street, or on a blind date, or, yes, in an elevator alone, she doesn’t know which group you’re in. You might be the potential best guy ever in the history of history, but there’s no way for her to know that. A fraction of men out there are most definitely not in that group. Which are you? Inside your head you know, but outside your head it’s impossible to.<ref>{{cite web|last=Plait |first=Phil |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2014/05/27/not_all_men_how_discussing_women_s_issues_gets_derailed.html |title=Not All Men: How Discussing Women’s Issues Gets Derailed; |publisher=Slate.com |date=2014-05-27 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref>}}In a differing opinion, [[India Times]] writer Sumeet Keswani writes that the statement "does not serve to derail the feminism movement; it seeks to draw the line between feminism and [[misandry]]."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Keswani|first1=Suweet|title=Why #NotAllMen is part of the feminist movement, not against it|url=http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sumeet-keswani-blog/why-notallmen-is-part-of-the-feminist-movement-not-against-it/|website=indiatimes.com|publisher=India Times|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>

